1
00:13:05,690 --> 00:13:08,818
<i>What I appreciate about India
is that it is a democracy...</i>

2
00:13:08,960 --> 00:13:11,258
<i>...with a transparent legal system.</i>

3
00:13:11,762 --> 00:13:16,062
<i>If you buy a plot of land,
you can be sure it is yours.</i>

4
00:13:16,534 --> 00:13:18,593
<i>Nobody will take it from you
tomorrow...</i>

5
00:13:18,736 --> 00:13:22,331
<i>...by demanding new taxes
or trying to confiscate it otherwise.</i>

6
00:13:22,840 --> 00:13:26,867
These are the remnants
of the colonial era.

7
00:13:29,613 --> 00:13:32,275
This legal system is
very important for me.

8
00:13:32,583 --> 00:13:35,711
It's an important
investment criterion.

9
00:13:38,456 --> 00:13:39,684
We are very satisfied with it.

10
00:13:57,808 --> 00:14:00,641
<i>My name is Mirko Kovats,
I am Austrian.</i>

11
00:14:00,878 --> 00:14:04,746
<i>I built up one of the biggest
Austrian industrial groups...</i>

12
00:14:05,483 --> 00:14:06,814
<i>...over the past ten years.</i>

13
00:14:06,951 --> 00:14:09,715
Nobody is calling for the state here.

14
00:14:10,821 --> 00:14:13,187
You have to take care of yourself.

15
00:14:20,264 --> 00:14:24,325
I am always astonished
to hear discussions at home...

16
00:14:25,236 --> 00:14:27,830
...about the problems
we think we have.

17
00:14:28,406 --> 00:14:30,533
They never stop discussing...

18
00:14:30,674 --> 00:14:33,404
...how to take things away
from people by taxing them.

19
00:14:33,544 --> 00:14:35,205
All that does not count here.

20
00:14:35,346 --> 00:14:36,938
The only thing that counts here
is the economy.

21
00:14:54,565 --> 00:14:56,362
<i>My name is Sujatha Raaju.</i>

22
00:14:56,834 --> 00:15:00,634
<i>I have completed commerce studies
from the Madras University.</i>

23
00:15:02,139 --> 00:15:06,508
<i>We are here in Chennai,
one of the biggest cities in India.</i>

24
00:15:06,677 --> 00:15:08,702
<i>It was formally known as Madras.</i>

25
00:15:09,280 --> 00:15:11,680
<i>It is populated
with 8 million people.</i>

26
00:15:12,450 --> 00:15:16,181
One third of the population
lead a life like this.

27
00:15:17,288 --> 00:15:20,086
That is, they live
on the banks of the rivers.

28
00:15:20,224 --> 00:15:23,387
Some of them live
even a much poorer life...

29
00:15:23,894 --> 00:15:25,521
...living on the pavements.

30
00:15:47,885 --> 00:15:51,321
In Europe students are interested
in sociology.

31
00:15:51,455 --> 00:15:53,582
Everybody wants
to become a teacher.

32
00:15:55,159 --> 00:15:57,150
Here they are studying
engineering.

33
00:15:57,795 --> 00:16:00,958
<i>I ask myself who will be where
in 10 or 20 years.</i>

34
00:16:01,198 --> 00:16:02,790
<i>Will they be richer?</i>

35
00:16:02,933 --> 00:16:04,400
<i>Will we be poorer?</i>

36
00:16:05,102 --> 00:16:06,535
<i>I hope not.</i>

37
00:16:19,884 --> 00:16:23,479
<i>The people
who finance the company are...</i>

38
00:16:23,821 --> 00:16:26,619
<i>- As always if you have a company
quoted on the stock market...</i>

39
00:16:26,757 --> 00:16:29,385
<i>...investors from London,
who manage the money...</i>

40
00:16:29,627 --> 00:16:33,529
<i>...in pension funds and insurances.</i>

41
00:16:36,367 --> 00:16:38,232
<i>The factory is already too small.</i>

42
00:16:38,369 --> 00:16:42,032
<i>We think about moving and
enlarging it to the fourfold size.</i>

43
00:17:11,001 --> 00:17:13,401
<i>Competition forces us
to take measures...</i>

44
00:17:14,004 --> 00:17:15,972
<i>...all very unpleasant.</i>

45
00:17:16,106 --> 00:17:20,736
<i>But we are under pressure
from globalization.</i>

46
00:17:21,478 --> 00:17:23,946
<i>We have to compete with people...</i>

47
00:17:24,381 --> 00:17:27,680
<i>...who get very small wages...</i>

48
00:17:28,319 --> 00:17:30,446
<i>...but have to earn their living.</i>

49
00:17:32,256 --> 00:17:35,692
<i>Of course,
working hours will become longer.</i>

50
00:17:35,826 --> 00:17:41,594
<i>I am sure that this overtime
will not be paid.</i>

51
00:17:42,333 --> 00:17:44,995
<i>It is quite simple,
we have to work more.</i>

52
00:17:45,135 --> 00:17:46,966
<i>We have no choice.</i>

53
00:17:48,305 --> 00:17:49,863
Very tidy.

54
00:17:51,875 --> 00:17:53,843
Was this difficult to achieve?

55
00:17:55,579 --> 00:17:58,139
I had to put a lot of effort into it.

56
00:17:58,282 --> 00:18:01,274
But it works, as we see.

57
00:18:05,322 --> 00:18:07,085
I am really astonished.

58
00:18:08,592 --> 00:18:10,890
Are you having any discussions
with labour unions?

59
00:18:11,028 --> 00:18:12,791
Fortunately not, up to now.

60
00:18:13,731 --> 00:18:16,393
I try to take into account...

61
00:18:16,533 --> 00:18:18,763
...our employees' social situation.

62
00:18:18,902 --> 00:18:20,164
How much does a welder earn?

63
00:18:20,304 --> 00:18:25,469
The equivalent of
200 euros a month on average.

64
00:18:25,609 --> 00:18:27,577
That's what he earns?
Or what he costs?

65
00:18:27,711 --> 00:18:29,008
That is what he earns.

66
00:18:29,146 --> 00:18:31,307
He costs us about 25% more.

67
00:18:31,682 --> 00:18:33,047
250.

68
00:18:33,317 --> 00:18:34,909
What about an engineer?

69
00:18:35,219 --> 00:18:37,813
Around 8-10 times more.

70
00:18:38,422 --> 00:18:40,652
That makes 2500.

71
00:18:40,791 --> 00:18:43,453
That is far below Europe...

72
00:18:43,594 --> 00:18:46,722
...but not cheap any more.

73
00:18:46,864 --> 00:18:51,699
You have to consider
the booming markets in India.

74
00:18:51,835 --> 00:18:56,238
The price increase
will not only be 3-5%...

75
00:18:56,373 --> 00:18:58,933
...but 10-15% in the next years.

76
00:18:59,076 --> 00:19:02,603
That's something
to take into account in future.

77
00:19:03,080 --> 00:19:05,913
That means we have to be efficient.

78
00:19:06,050 --> 00:19:09,213
We can't afford to be generous.

79
00:19:09,353 --> 00:19:10,411
The costs will increase.

80
00:19:10,554 --> 00:19:14,615
<i>I worked in order to minimize
the processes...</i>

81
00:19:15,159 --> 00:19:17,525
...and to reduce the additional costs.

82
00:19:17,728 --> 00:19:21,164
We invested
in half automated production...

83
00:19:21,665 --> 00:19:25,761
...in order to reduce the costs
or keep them low.

84
00:20:02,673 --> 00:20:06,302
We have to buy it at any price.

85
00:20:06,443 --> 00:20:08,673
It will only become more expensive.

86
00:20:08,946 --> 00:20:11,642
The prices won't fall.

87
00:20:30,834 --> 00:20:32,392
<i>Indians pay their taxes.</i>

88
00:20:33,437 --> 00:20:36,736
<i>Taxes are collected by the government
in form of sales tax...</i>

89
00:20:36,874 --> 00:20:39,866
<i>...revenue tax, water tax,
electricity tax...</i>

90
00:20:40,244 --> 00:20:42,769
<i>...property tax
and so many other taxes...</i>

91
00:20:42,913 --> 00:20:45,143
<i>...that are collected
by the government.</i>

92
00:20:45,449 --> 00:20:48,213
<i>But this revenue
is given to foreign investors...</i>

93
00:20:48,352 --> 00:20:50,115
<i>...in the form of grants.</i>

94
00:20:50,621 --> 00:20:53,055
<i>And the government lacks
the money...</i>

95
00:20:53,190 --> 00:20:56,216
<i>...to take care of the social welfare
of the people.</i>

96
00:22:46,637 --> 00:22:51,438
<i>Environmental and social standards
will not change for a long time.</i>

97
00:22:52,209 --> 00:22:55,645
The costs to raise these standards...

98
00:22:55,779 --> 00:23:00,148
...cannot be paid by countries
like India or China.

99
00:23:00,284 --> 00:23:02,684
This is reality - Like it or not.

100
00:23:03,320 --> 00:23:05,015
The majority of people are poor.

101
00:23:06,089 --> 00:23:09,354
And they will stay poor
for a long time.

102
00:23:09,760 --> 00:23:11,990
They have to stay competitive
at any price.

103
00:23:12,129 --> 00:23:17,066
Therefore, I think that, except
for soft declarations of good will...

104
00:23:17,200 --> 00:23:21,637
...things won't change much
over the next decades...

105
00:23:21,772 --> 00:23:26,232
...because people can't afford it.

106
00:23:30,647 --> 00:23:32,842
<i>Flourishing economic growth
has nothing to do...</i>

107
00:23:32,983 --> 00:23:35,042
<i>...with the people or the society.</i>

108
00:23:38,088 --> 00:23:41,683
<i>Economic growth is only for
the politician, for the investor...</i>

109
00:23:41,825 --> 00:23:44,988
<i>...and for the middleman
who plays between them.</i>

110
00:23:46,229 --> 00:23:48,663
<i>10 years ago,
in a middleclass family...</i>

111
00:23:48,799 --> 00:23:51,233
<i>...if the income of the family
was around 10000...</i>

112
00:23:51,368 --> 00:23:55,031
<i>...they were able to save
at least 2000 to 3000 rupees.</i>

113
00:23:55,172 --> 00:23:57,037
<i>But those days are gone.</i>

114
00:23:58,008 --> 00:24:00,067
<i>Today, even if they earn 20000...</i>

115
00:24:00,210 --> 00:24:02,838
<i>...they are not able to save
a single penny.</i>

116
00:24:03,580 --> 00:24:06,879
<i>There is a lot of foreign culture
in India...</i>

117
00:24:07,017 --> 00:24:09,042
<i>...and people are getting
accustomed to it...</i>

118
00:24:09,186 --> 00:24:13,122
<i>...following all the ways
to imitate the Western culture.</i>

119
00:24:13,624 --> 00:24:15,888
<i>But poverty
has not been eradicated.</i>

120
00:24:16,026 --> 00:24:17,960
<i>There are still poor people.</i>

121
00:24:18,528 --> 00:24:20,018
<i>This can be eradicated only...</i>

122
00:24:20,163 --> 00:24:22,654
<i>...if there is a good political system
in India.</i>

123
00:24:52,829 --> 00:24:54,456
<i>My name is Kalaiselvan.</i>

124
00:24:54,665 --> 00:24:56,963
<i>I am in the 7th class,
I am 12 years old.</i>

125
00:24:57,234 --> 00:24:59,794
<i>I have been living in the slum
Gandhinagar since I was born.</i>

126
00:24:59,936 --> 00:25:02,461
<i>When I am grown up,
I want to be a lawyer...</i>

127
00:25:03,674 --> 00:25:06,609
<i>...and I want
to fight against corruption.</i>

128
00:27:47,070 --> 00:27:48,662
<i>My name is Gerhard Schwarz.</i>

129
00:27:48,805 --> 00:27:51,831
<i>For 14 years,
I have been chief editor...</i>

130
00:27:51,975 --> 00:27:54,910
<i>...of the economic section
of Neue Zürcher Zeitung.</i>

131
00:27:55,779 --> 00:28:00,773
<i>I also teach
at the University of Zurich.</i>

132
00:28:02,185 --> 00:28:07,316
<i>Besides, I am President...</i>

133
00:28:07,457 --> 00:28:10,949
<i>...of the Friedrich August
Hayek-Society.</i>

134
00:28:11,127 --> 00:28:15,257
<i>Friedrich August von Hayek
was certainly...</i>

135
00:28:15,398 --> 00:28:19,391
<i>...the most important liberal economist
of the 20th century.</i>

136
00:28:19,703 --> 00:28:22,103
<i>He was born in Austria...</i>

137
00:28:22,239 --> 00:28:25,902
<i>...and worked in England,
America and Germany.</i>

138
00:28:35,151 --> 00:28:39,144
<i>We are on our way from vevey
on Lake Geneva...</i>

139
00:28:39,623 --> 00:28:41,648
...to Mont Pèlerin.

140
00:28:42,425 --> 00:28:45,292
Meaning "Pilgrim's Mount".

141
00:28:45,695 --> 00:28:50,598
It is a little village
with some big hotels.

142
00:28:52,035 --> 00:28:57,268
In 1947 some of the most important...

143
00:28:57,741 --> 00:29:02,610
European and American thinkers
met here...

144
00:29:03,546 --> 00:29:07,949
...to reflect upon the future
of the Western World.

145
00:29:30,373 --> 00:29:35,310
<i>The Mont Pèlerin Society was founded
in this "Hotel du Parc".</i>

146
00:29:36,546 --> 00:29:39,674
<i>The founders' goal was
to organize...</i>

147
00:29:39,816 --> 00:29:42,182
<i>...an intellectual network.</i>

148
00:29:42,886 --> 00:29:46,287
<i>They did not want to make politics...</i>

149
00:29:46,423 --> 00:29:50,484
<i>...but wanted to influence politics
with their ideas.</i>

150
00:29:51,494 --> 00:29:56,591
<i>The Mont Pèlerin Society
became famous in the 1980s...</i>

151
00:29:56,733 --> 00:29:58,530
...with Ronald Reagan.

152
00:29:59,369 --> 00:30:02,861
In his government
and in his advisory team...

153
00:30:03,006 --> 00:30:06,908
...there was a great number of members
of the Mont Pèlerin Society.

154
00:30:08,411 --> 00:30:13,439
Sometimes 20 or even more members.

155
00:30:13,783 --> 00:30:19,346
Approximately at the same time
Margaret Thatcher...

156
00:30:20,657 --> 00:30:25,685
...drew on Hayek's ideas...

157
00:30:25,829 --> 00:30:28,889
...and the ideas of British members...

158
00:30:29,032 --> 00:30:32,263
<i>...of the Mont Pèlerin Society.</i>

159
00:34:45,989 --> 00:34:48,549
<i>Here we are at the entrance
of the Sahel.</i>

160
00:34:49,892 --> 00:34:51,689
<i>All the soils are ruined.</i>

161
00:34:52,829 --> 00:34:56,230
<i>There is total erosion,
even ravines.</i>

162
00:34:57,000 --> 00:34:59,628
<i>This is the result
of the cotton monoculture.</i>

163
00:35:03,139 --> 00:35:04,504
The cotton is gone...

164
00:35:05,375 --> 00:35:07,138
...the money for the cotton is gone.

165
00:35:08,077 --> 00:35:11,740
The only thing left is this soil,
where you can't cultivate anything.

166
00:35:13,316 --> 00:35:16,285
I am called Yves Delisle.

167
00:35:17,654 --> 00:35:19,849
I am an agronomist by profession.

168
00:35:22,125 --> 00:35:26,459
I studied
Development Studies in Geneva.

169
00:35:30,500 --> 00:35:36,097
I have been working directly
with farmers for about 20 years.

170
00:35:39,008 --> 00:35:42,375
20 years is quite a long time.

171
00:35:43,313 --> 00:35:46,840
But up to now,
I have the impression...

172
00:35:46,983 --> 00:35:50,316
...that the situation
has not improved.

173
00:36:35,698 --> 00:36:40,135
<i>These people earn
not even 50 euros a year.</i>

174
00:36:59,255 --> 00:37:01,086
We are anxious!

175
00:37:01,424 --> 00:37:04,120
We are fed up.

176
00:37:04,260 --> 00:37:07,593
Our children cultivate cotton,
but they don't get anything for it.

177
00:37:07,730 --> 00:37:09,789
What shall we do?

178
00:37:10,199 --> 00:37:12,497
We are reduced to doing nothing.
We hope for your help.

179
00:37:12,635 --> 00:37:14,193
To improve our lives.

180
00:37:14,337 --> 00:37:17,067
Go and tell those
who buy the cotton to help us...

181
00:37:17,206 --> 00:37:20,175
...to buy the cotton at a fair price.

182
00:37:20,309 --> 00:37:24,837
So that Burkina and we
get more money.

183
00:37:26,048 --> 00:37:29,540
Old women like me work the whole
day long under the sun. For nothing.

184
00:37:30,353 --> 00:37:31,843
But what can we do?

185
00:37:31,954 --> 00:37:34,013
Try to understand us.

186
00:37:34,891 --> 00:37:36,791
We beg you.

187
00:37:37,393 --> 00:37:38,883
You see how tiring the work is.

188
00:37:39,028 --> 00:37:41,861
If we managed to pay back
our loans, we would be glad.

189
00:38:19,135 --> 00:38:21,933
<i>The quality of cotton is the best
in the world.</i>

190
00:38:22,405 --> 00:38:25,340
<i>The production costs
are the lowest.</i>

191
00:38:25,875 --> 00:38:29,106
<i>The cotton is clean,
because all is done by hand.</i>

192
00:38:31,047 --> 00:38:34,278
<i>Nevertheless, the price is very low
on the world market.</i>

193
00:39:30,039 --> 00:39:34,669
<i>Every year, the USA subsidize
their cotton producers...</i>

194
00:39:34,810 --> 00:39:37,040
<i>...with $3 billion.</i>

195
00:39:37,547 --> 00:39:40,107
If the Americans are liberal,
so be it!

196
00:39:40,249 --> 00:39:42,183
<i>But why do they subsidize
their cotton producers?</i>

197
00:39:43,553 --> 00:39:45,020
This isn't liberalism!

198
00:39:45,154 --> 00:39:46,781
In reality,
they practise protectionism...

199
00:39:46,923 --> 00:39:48,618
...and impose liberalism on us.

200
00:39:49,325 --> 00:39:50,485
They apply two different standards!

201
00:39:50,626 --> 00:39:53,060
It is like if you have a football field
and two teams.

202
00:39:53,195 --> 00:39:58,531
Team A has the best shoes
and can also use their hands.

203
00:39:58,668 --> 00:40:02,229
Team B - And these are the Africans,
and small countries like us...

204
00:40:02,371 --> 00:40:05,636
...have to play
without shoes or hands.

205
00:40:05,775 --> 00:40:07,436
Do you consider this
to be normal?

206
00:40:34,503 --> 00:40:38,269
<i>In the 1980s the World Bank imposed...</i>

207
00:40:38,407 --> 00:40:41,171
<i>...restructuring programmes
on Burkina Faso.</i>

208
00:40:41,677 --> 00:40:43,668
<i>What does this mean for the country?</i>

209
00:40:44,947 --> 00:40:46,676
<i>Raw materials are exported...</i>

210
00:40:47,216 --> 00:40:49,514
<i>...cotton in the form of raw cotton...</i>

211
00:40:49,652 --> 00:40:50,914
<i>...without added value.</i>

212
00:40:54,323 --> 00:40:58,020
<i>All the World Bank and the investors
are interested in...</i>

213
00:40:58,160 --> 00:41:01,755
<i>...is sucking raw materials
out of the country.</i>

214
00:41:02,198 --> 00:41:06,601
<i>Cotton, timber, coffee, cacao, gold,
and so on.</i>

215
00:41:08,270 --> 00:41:11,364
<i>In the past, the colonialists forced us
to cultivate a certain product.</i>

216
00:41:12,208 --> 00:41:15,541
<i>Now the World Bank
puts us under pressure...</i>

217
00:41:15,678 --> 00:41:19,170
<i>...with money to plant cotton.</i>

218
00:41:34,296 --> 00:41:36,662
<i>How can you buy medicine?</i>

219
00:41:38,334 --> 00:41:40,199
<i>You need foreign currency.</i>

220
00:41:40,336 --> 00:41:43,430
<i>The cotton can bring us
this foreign currency.</i>

221
00:41:45,007 --> 00:41:50,035
<i>I told you that cotton makes the living
of two million people - Directly.</i>

222
00:41:50,179 --> 00:41:52,238
<i>But if you calculate that in Africa...</i>

223
00:41:52,381 --> 00:41:57,318
<i>...every person supports
another 15 people...</i>

224
00:41:57,453 --> 00:41:59,887
<i>...multiply by 2 million...</i>

225
00:42:00,022 --> 00:42:03,150
<i>...and you quickly realize that
the whole population lives off cotton.</i>

226
00:42:04,627 --> 00:42:07,824
<i>If the USA did not subsidize
their cotton...</i>

227
00:42:08,464 --> 00:42:11,160
<i>Burkina Faso would make profits...</i>

228
00:42:11,400 --> 00:42:13,630
<i>...of at least 80 billion CFA a year.</i>

229
00:42:15,905 --> 00:42:17,896
<i>The bilateral aid...</i>

230
00:42:18,708 --> 00:42:21,336
<i>...the credits from the EU...</i>

231
00:42:21,477 --> 00:42:23,468
<i>USA and Japan...</i>

232
